Tricia Payne scored 21 points, including
five 3-pointers, as Texas Christian posted a 70-53 upset of Vanderbilt (No. 8 ESPN/USA Today; No. 9 Associated Press) on Saturday night.
article.headline: Cold-shooting Commodores down from the start
article.linkText: From the start, TCU runs away from No. 9 Vandy
article.story:
FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) -- If TCU head coach Jeff Mittie took any satisfaction in upsetting  Vanderbilt (No. 8 ESPN/USA Today; No. 9 Associated Press), he sure didn't show it.

"We appreciate the victory because it's something that's never happened around here,'' Mittie said after TCU won 70-53 Saturday night. "But it's something we have to forget about it at midnight and turn our attention to our next opponent.''

Tricia Payne scored 21 points, including five 3-pointers, as the Lady Frogs (5-5) picked up their first victory ever against a top-10 team.

It also was their first against a ranked opponent since beating Penn State in the 2001 NCAA Tournament. They had lost four games against ranked teams this season.
	
The Commodores (7-2) came into the game leading the nation in
field-goal percentage but shot just 39 percent (19-of-49) and
committed 20 turnovers. They scored 101 points in a victory last
Sunday against Tennessee-Martin.

"Their defensive pressure really put us on our heels,'' Vanderbilt coach Melanie Balcomb said. "They came out more aggressive and physical than we did.''

The Lady Frogs led 34-21 at halftime and put the game away with
a 12-0 spurt for a 52-25 cushion with 14:21 left. Payne and Ebony
Shaw scored six points each in the run. The Commodores got no
closer than 15 points the rest of the way.

"We knew we had the potential to play a game like this,'' Payne said. "We just had to put it all together for 40 minutes.''

TCU also had a 15-0 run in the first half, holding Vanderbilt
scoreless for nearly seven minutes to turn a 4-2 deficit into a
17-4 lead. Sandora Irvin's putback and Candace Baldwin's layup
capped the run.

The Lady Frogs stretched their lead to 34-16 on a Payne 3-pointer before the Commodores closed out the half with five straight points.

"We came out scared,'' said Vanderbilt center Chantelle
Anderson, who led Vanderbilt with 19 points and 10 rebounds. "We
backed away from their pressure and let them push us around.''

Payne, who was 5-of-9 from 3-point range, became the fifth player in TCU history to score 1,000 points in her career. She now has 1,010 points.

Hillary Hager added 10 points for Vanderbilt. Shaw scored 12 points for TCU.
